Piping

The basic idea here is to adopt the unix pipe model for groups w/implications for interpreter syntax
    blockA = block1 | block2 | block3;
Which could be rewritten as
    blockA = block3(block2(block1()));
Then add block4 and
    blockA = block1 | block2 | block3 | block4;
becomes
    blockA = block4(block3(block2(block1())));

From parser perspective, given block1, fire its method and then deal with what it produces (a block). If there is a following pipe, pass the result to the block method following the pipe.
With a pipe there is a supplier and a receiver, altho the supplier is null at the beginning of the pipe and the receiver is null at the end, leaving the last result as the result of the expression.
    
    So how does this work? If a block has a method, it fires it producing a result.
    If a block is a rule, if first checks its input, if the input matches the rule, the rule method fires producing a result.
    May not be efficient. It just has to work. If we dispense w/the pipes, that is: | and then treat each block as an instruction to be fired in order taking the output of the previous instruction as input then the result is the same, altho the syntax might not be apparent. This conflates operator (method) w/operand (block).
    Take a + block that adds everything passed into it (presumably starts out null) into it (such that it is its own result)

Given a pipeline as described above HWF, then add a stream, which is a list of blocks such that
    block1 block2 block3 | +block | block4;
The first three blocks here are a stream passed in order to the +block to be added with the result passed on to block4 - So how does a stream work? Perhaps a stream is a block w/members to be iterated over, however, who does the iteration? The parser which translates the above into
        block1 | +block;
        block2 | +block;
        block3 | +block | block4;
    It looks like the | operator is a shortcut means to pass an argument to a method (not so different from operator overloads in Tok - worth a shot)
Syntactically do not like the stream of blocks, looking at it, which comes first? Alternatively, if the blocks are all components of a parent then it looks like blocks1-3 | +block | block4 No ambiguity
How about a gather syntax? block1-3 += block1 block2 block3; would add 3 components to block1-3. The parser would have to figure out that block1 block2 block3 are a list and we would need an add(list) method in GroupItem. The notion of a list argument would have to be added to Tok. If there is no list method then Tok would generate
        block1-3 += block1
        block1-3 += block2
        block1-3 += block3
    probably good enough even if brute force. May not need it because ParseXML does it well w/no special syntax

For now forget any interpreter. With what we got we can define rules w/methods written in Tok. What do we end up with? A bunch of compiled methods that need to be linked to the blocks/rules that contain them, if we could do this as a jit, it would be ideal, if not we end up with a linkage process. plg already does this sort of stuff, only in the case of compiling a single block, all the rule building that happens in a parser's setRule method can be simpler. Declare a block, assign its method and we done. In the case of multiple blocks, do it again. This does not need to happen in the same program. The program can be a set of methods generated when the block rule was parsed.
    
